# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: android-jni
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:android-jni/bytecode] The name *bytecode* stems from instruction sets that have one-byte opcodes followed by optional parameters.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Intermediate representations such as bytecode may be output by programming language implementations to ease interpretation, or it may be used to reduce hardware and operating system dependence by allowing the same code to run cross-platform, on different devices.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Bytecode may often be either directly executed on a virtual machine (a p-code machine, i.e., interpreter), or it may be further compiled into machine code for better performance.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Since bytecode instructions are processed by software, they may be arbitrarily complex, but are nonetheless often akin to traditional hardware instructions: virtual stack machines are the most common, but virtual register machines have been built also.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Different parts may often be stored in separate files, similar to object modules, but dynamically loaded during execution.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] A bytecode program may be executed by parsing and *directly* executing the instructions, one at a time.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] This kind of *bytecode interpreter* is very portable.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Some systems, called dynamic translators, or *just-in-time* (JIT) compilers, translate bytecode into machine code as necessary at runtime.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] This makes the virtual machine hardware-specific but does not lose the portability of the bytecode.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] For example, Java and Smalltalk code is typically stored in bytecode format, which is typically then JIT compiled to translate the bytecode to machine code before execution.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] This introduces a delay before a program is run, when the bytecode is compiled to native machine code, but improves execution speed considerably compared to interpreting source code directly, normally by around an order of magnitude (10x).
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Because of its performance advantage, today many language implementations execute a program in two phases, first compiling the source code into bytecode, and then passing the bytecode to the virtual machine.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] There are bytecode based virtual machines of this sort for Java, Raku, Python, PHP, Tcl, mawk and Forth (however, Forth is seldom compiled via bytecodes in this way, and its virtual machine is more generic instead).
[src:android-jni/bytecode] The implementation of Perl and Ruby 1.8 instead work by walking an abstract syntax tree representation derived from the source code.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] More recently, the authors of V8 and Dart have challenged the notion that intermediate bytecode is needed for fast and efficient VM implementation.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Both of these language implementations currently do direct JIT compiling from source code to machine code with no bytecode intermediary.
[src:android-jni/bytecode] Compiled code can be analysed and investigated using a built-in tool for debugging the low-level bytecode.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] A **foreign function interface** (**FFI**) is a mechanism by which a program written in one programming language can call interoperable routines or make use of services written or compiled in another one.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] An FFI is often used in contexts where calls are made into a binary dynamic-link library.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] The term comes from the specification for Common Lisp, which explicitly refers to the programming language feature enabling for inter-language calls as such; the term is also often used officially by the interpreter and compiler documentation for Haskell, Rust, PHP, Python, and LuaJIT (Lua).
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] Other languages use other terminology: Ada has *language bindings*, while Java has *Java Native Interface* (JNI), *Java Native Access* (JNA), or since Java 22, Foreign Function and Memory API.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] Foreign function interface has become generic terminology for mechanisms which provide such services.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] The primary function of a foreign function interface is to mate the semantics and calling conventions of one programming language (the *host* language, or the language which defines the FFI), with the semantics and conventions of another (the *guest* language).
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] This process must also take into consideration the runtime environments and application binary interfaces of both.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] C++ offers compatibility with C trivially, however as C++ uses name mangling, symbols that are to be exported in shared libraries must be wrapped in extern "C" blocks which prevent name mangling.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] `extern "C"` functions may call C++ code internally, but may only return C types and may not throw exceptions.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] Many FFIs can be generated automatically: for example, SWIG.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] However, in the case of an extension language a semantic inversion of the relationship of guest and host can occur, when a smaller body of extension language is the guest invoking services in the larger body of host language, such as writing a small plugin for GIMP.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] Some FFIs are restricted to free standing functions, while others also allow calls of functions embedded in an object or class (often called method calls); some even permit migration of complex datatypes or objects across the language boundary.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] In most cases, an FFI is defined by a higher-level language, so that it may employ services defined and implemented in a lower-level language, typically a system programming language like C or C++.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] This is typically done to either access operating system (OS) services in the language in which the OS API is defined, or for performance goals.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] Many FFIs also provide the means for the called language to invoke services in the host language also.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] The term foreign function interface is generally not used to describe multi-lingual runtimes such as the Microsoft Common Language Runtime, where a common *substrate* is provided which enables any CLR-compliant language to use services defined in any other.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] There are some special cases, in which the languages compile into the same bytecode VM, like Clojure and Java, as well as Elixir and Erlang.
[src:android-jni/foreign-function-interface] Since there is no interface, it is not an FFI, strictly speaking, while it offers the same functions to the user.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The **Java Native Interface** (or Native Method Interface) is a foreign function interface designed for non-Java programming frameworks.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Java 22 introduces the Foreign Function and Memory API, which can be seen as the successor to Java Native Interface.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] JNI allows native methods to allow for applications to make calls outside of the Java platform, e.g. when the standard Java class library does not support platform-specific features or a certain program library.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] It is also used to modify an existing application (written in another programming language) to be accessible to Java applications.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Many standard library classes depend on JNI to provide functionality to the developer and the user, such as file I/O and audio APIs.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Only applications and signed applets may invoke JNI.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The JNI framework allows native code to manipulate and consume Java objects.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] A native method (marked by the keyword `native` in Java) can create Java objects and inspect and use these objects to perform its tasks.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] A native method can also inspect and use objects created by Java application code.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] An application that relies on JNI loses the platform portability Java offers (a partial workaround is to write a separate implementation of JNI code for each platform and have Java detect the operating system and load the correct one at runtime).
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Not only can native code interface with Java, it can also draw on a Java `Canvas`, which is possible with the Java AWT Native Interface, available since J2SE 1.3.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] JNI also allows direct access to assembly, without a C bridge.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Accessing Java applications from assembly is possible in the same way.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The JNI is the entry point between languages used to begin the JVM startup.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Java types are the default primitive types available on Java, while JVM type signatures are identifiers used by the JVM to identify the type matching on Java, while native types are types defined by the JNI itself to map to native types.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] In addition, the JVM type signature `L*fully-qualified-class*;` refers the class uniquely specified by that name, for example the signature `Ljava.lang.String;` (`Ljava/lang/String;` in class files) refers to the class `java.lang.String`.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Prefixing `[` to the signature denotes an array of that type; for example, `[I` refers to `int[]`, and `[[I` refers to `int[][]`, up to a maximum of 255 dimensions.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] One can use `jint` where you normally use an `int`, and vice versa, without any typecasting required.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] However, mapping between Java strings and arrays to native strings and arrays is different; for instance, `jstring` and `char*` are not interchangeable types, nor are `jintArray` and `int[]`.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Here, all Java reference types are defined as opaque empty types which act as handles to Java objects.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Note however that `jfieldID` and `jmethodID` are just opaque handles, and do not correspond to `java.lang.reflect.Field`/`java.lang.reflect.Method`.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The communication between native code and Java code is intermediated by the JNI, acting as an ABI.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] `JNIEnv` is used to access the structure of functions (array of function pointers), and each function being identifiable by a unique pointer.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] According to the programming language, C or C++, the implementation can be a little different.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] In the JNI framework, native functions are implemented in separate .c or .cpp files (C++ provides a slightly simpler interface with JNI).
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] When the JVM invokes the function, it passes a `JNIEnv*`, a `jobject`, and any Java arguments declared by the Java method.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The `env` pointer is a structure that contains the interface to the JVM.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] It includes all of the functions necessary to interact with the JVM and to work with Java objects.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Anything that Java code can do can be done using `JNIEnv`.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The argument `obj` is a reference to the Java object inside which this native method has been declared.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Native data types can be mapped to/from Java data types.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] For compound types, such as objects, arrays and strings, the native code must explicitly convert the data by calling methods in the `JNIEnv`.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] A JNI environment pointer (`JNIEnv*`) is passed as an argument for each native function mapped to a Java method, allowing for interaction with the JNI environment within the native method.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] This JNI interface pointer can be stored, but remains valid only in the current thread.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Other threads must first call `AttachCurrentThread()` to attach themselves to the VM and obtain a JNI interface pointer.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Once attached, a native thread works like a regular Java thread running within a native method.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The native thread remains attached to the VM until it calls `DetachCurrentThread()` to detach itself.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The JNI framework does not provide any automatic garbage collection for non-JVM memory resources allocated by code executing on the native side.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Consequently, native code is responsible explicitly releasing all acquired resources.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] On Linux and Solaris platforms, if the native code registers itself as a signal handler, it can intercept signals intended for the JVM.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] A chain of responsibility can be used to allow native code to interoperate with the JVM.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The encoding used for the `NewStringUTF()`, `GetStringUTFLength()`, `GetStringUTFChars()`, `ReleaseStringUTFChars()` and `GetStringUTFRegion()` functions is "modified UTF-8", which is not valid UTF-8 for all inputs, but a different encoding.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The null character (U+0000) and codepoints not on the Basic Multilingual Plane (greater than or equal to U+10000, i.e. those represented as surrogate pairs in UTF-16) are encoded differently in modified UTF-8.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Many programs actually use these functions incorrectly and treat the UTF-8 strings returned or passed into the functions as standard UTF-8 strings instead of modified UTF-8 strings.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Java 22 introduced the Foreign Function and Memory API, located in `java.lang.foreign` which can be seen as a sort of successor to the Java Native Interface.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] It has a simpler interface and generally requires less boilerplate than JNI, due to no longer requiring the inclusion of `<jni.h>` in the foreign library to invoke, and Foreign Function and Memory API abstracts away the usage of the `native` keyword completely.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] It supports region-based memory management.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Primitives receive `ValueLayout.JAVA_*` layouts when mapped to their native types, while pointer types use `ValueLayout.ADDRESS` (for instance `char*`, `int**` or `struct Point*`).
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Additionally, the constant `MemorySegment.NULL` (of type `java.lang.foreign.MemorySegment`) is a zero-length native segment representing a null address (`nullptr`), equivalent to `MemorySegment.ofAddress(0)`.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Java offers additional methods to express more complicated native types.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The Java Runtime Interface was created by Netscape as a precursor.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Microsoft's proprietary implementation of a Java Virtual Machine (Visual J++) had a similar mechanism for calling native code from Java, called the Raw Native Interface (RNI).
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] In addition, it offered a simple way to call existing native code that was not itself aware of Java, such as (but not limited to) the Windows API, (J/Direct).
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] However, following the Sun–Microsoft litigation about this implementation, Visual J++ ceased to be maintained.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] RNI was simpler to use than JNI, because no management of the Java environment pointer was needed; instead, all Java objects were accessed directly.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] To facilitate this, a tool was used to generate header files from Java classes.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Similarly, J/Direct was easier to use than using the necessary intermediate native library and JNI.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Java Native Access (JNA) is a community-developed library that provides Java programmers easy access to native shared libraries without using JNI.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] However, this requires the redistribution of the dependent jar library.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] The tradeoff is between JNI being more complex and JNA being slower, and not built-in like JNI.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Historically, GCC (until GCC 7) offered the GNU Compiler for Java.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] This compiler offered the Compiled Native Interface (CNI), which allowed direct interoperability between C++ and Java.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] It provided an API that was heavily based off of JNI itself.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] It claimed several advantages over JNI, as it represented Java classes directly as C++ classes.
[src:android-jni/java-native-interface] Since Java 22, the Foreign Function and Memory API supersedes the JNI, due to its reduced boilerplate and simplified interface.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] In programming and software design, a **binding** is an application programming interface (API) that provides glue code specifically made to allow a programming language to use a foreign library or operating system service (one that is not native to that language).
[src:android-jni/language-binding] Binding generally refers to a mapping of one thing to another.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] In the context of software libraries, bindings are wrapper libraries that bridge two programming languages, so that a library written for one language can be used in another language.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] Many software libraries are written in system programming languages such as C or C++.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] To use such libraries from another language, usually of higher-level, such as Java, Common Lisp, Scheme, Python, or Lua, a binding to the library must be created in that language, possibly requiring recompiling the language's code, depending on the amount of modification needed.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] However, most languages offer a foreign function interface, such as Python's and OCaml's `ctypes`, and Embeddable Common Lisp's `cffi` and `uffi`.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] For example, Python bindings are used when an extant C library, written for some purpose, is to be used from Python.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] Another example is `libsvn` which is written in C to provide an API to access the Subversion software repository.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] To access Subversion from within Java code, `libsvnjavahl` can be used, which depends on `libsvn` being installed and acts as a bridge between the language Java and `libsvn`, thus providing an API that invokes functions from `libsvn` to do the work.
[src:android-jni/language-binding] Major motives to create library bindings include software reuse, to reduce reimplementing a library in several languages, and the difficulty of implementing some algorithms efficiently in some high-level languages.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Linux OpenGL drivers are split in two: a kernel-driver and a user-space driver.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The user-space driver does all the translation of OpenGL commands into machine code to be submitted to the GPU.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] To reduce the number of system calls, the user-space driver implements marshalling.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] If the GPU's command buffer is full of rendering data, the API could simply store the requested rendering call in a temporary buffer and, when the command buffer is close to being empty, it can perform a switch to kernel-mode and add a number of stored commands all at once.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling data requires some kind of data transfer, which leverages a specific data format to be chosen as the serialization target.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] XML is one such format and means of transferring data between systems.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Microsoft, for example, uses it as the basis of the file formats of the various components (Word, Excel, Access, PowerPoint, etc.) of the Microsoft Office suite (see Office Open XML).
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] While this typically results in a verbose wire format, XML's fully-bracketed "start-tag", "end-tag" syntax allows provision of more accurate diagnostics and easier recovery from transmission or disk errors.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] In addition, because the tags occur repeatedly, one can use standard compression methods to shrink the content—all the Office file formats are created by zipping the raw XML.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Alternative formats such as JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are more concise, but correspondingly less robust for error recovery.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Once the data is transferred to a program or an application, it needs to be converted back to an object for usage.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, unmarshalling is generally used in the receiver end of the implementations of Remote Method Invocation (RMI) and Remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms to unmarshal transmitted objects in an executable form.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB or Java Architecture for XML Binding is the most common framework used by developers to marshal and unmarshal Java objects.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB provides for the interconversion between fundamental data types supported by Java and standard XML schema data types.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` is the framework used by C# developers to marshal and unmarshal C# objects.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] One of the advantages of C# over Java is that C# natively supports marshalling due to the inclusion of `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` class.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Java, on the other hand requires a non-native glue code in the form of JAXB to support marshalling.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] An example of unmarshalling is the conversion of an XML representation of an object to the default representation of the object in any programming language.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshalling is the process of converting the XML representation to the default executable Java representation, and running that very code to get a consistent, live object back.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Had a different format been chosen, the unmarshalling process would have been different, but the end result in the target runtime would be the same.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The process of unmarshalling XML data into an executable Java object is taken care of by the in-built `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` (formally `javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller`) class.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods defined in the `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` class are overloaded to accept XML from different types of input such as a `java.io.File`, `java.io.FileInputStream`, or `java.net.URL`.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshal methods can deserialize an entire XML document or a small part of it.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] When the XML root element is globally declared, these methods utilize the `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext`'s mapping of XML root elements to JAXB mapped classes to initiate the unmarshalling.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] If the mappings are not sufficient and the root elements are declared locally, the unmarshal methods use `declaredType` methods for the unmarshalling process.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] These two approaches can be understood below.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal method uses `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext`) to unmarshal the XML data, when the root element is globally declared.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` object always maintains a mapping of the globally declared XML element and its name to a JAXB mapped class.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] If the XML element name or its `@xsi:type` attribute matches the JAXB mapped class, the unmarshal method transforms the XML data using the appropriate JAXB mapped class.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the XML element name has no match, the unmarshal process will abort and throw an `jakarta.xml.bind.UnmarshalException` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.UnmarshalException`).
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] This can be avoided by using the unmarshal by `declaredType` methods.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] When the root element is not declared globally, the application assists the unmarshaller by application-provided mapping using `declaredType` parameters.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] By an order of precedence, even if the root name has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, the `declaredType` overrides the mapping.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the `@xsi:type` attribute of the XML data has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, then this takes precedence over declaredType parameter.
[src:android-jni/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods by `declaredType` parameters always return a `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBElement<T>` instance.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] A **software development kit** (**SDK**) is a collection of software development tools in one installable package.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] They facilitate the creation of applications by having a compiler, debugger and sometimes a software framework.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] They are normally specific to a hardware platform and operating system combination.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] To create applications with advanced functionalities such as advertisements, push notifications, etc., most application software developers use specific software development kits.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] Some SDKs are required for developing a platform-specific app.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] For example, the development of an Android app on the Java platform requires a Java Development Kit.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] For iOS applications (apps) the iOS SDK is required.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] For Universal Windows Platform the .NET Framework SDK might be used.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] There are also SDKs that add additional features and can be installed in apps to provide analytics, data about application activity, and monetization options.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] Some prominent creators of these types of SDKs include Google, Smaato, InMobi, and Facebook.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] An SDK can take the form of application programming interfaces in the form of on-device libraries of reusable functions used to interface to a particular programming language, or it may be as complex as hardware-specific tools that can communicate with a particular embedded system.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] Common tools include debugging facilities and other utilities, often presented in an integrated development environment.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] SDKs may include sample software and/or technical notes along with documentation, and tutorials to help clarify points made by the primary reference material.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] Platform SDKs may be distributed as multiple installable components rather than as a single monolithic package.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] For example, the Android SDK is composed of multiple packages required for app development, and its `sdkmanager` command-line tool can view, install, update and uninstall SDK packages.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] Microsoft's Windows SDK similarly includes platform headers, libraries, Windows Runtime metadata and build tools for developing Windows applications.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] SDKs often include licenses that make them unsuitable for building software intended to be developed under an incompatible license.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] For example, a proprietary SDK is generally incompatible with free software development, while a GNU General Public License'd SDK could be incompatible with proprietary software development, for legal reasons.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] However, SDKs built under the GNU Lesser General Public License are typically usable for proprietary development.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] In cases where the underlying technology is new, SDKs may include hardware.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] For example, AirTag's 2012 near-field communication SDK included both the paying and the reading halves of the necessary hardware stack.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] The average Android mobile app implements 15.6 separate SDKs, with gaming apps implementing on average 17.5 different SDKs.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] The most popular SDK categories for Android mobile apps are analytics and advertising.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] SDKs can be unsafe (because they are implemented within apps yet run separate code).
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] Malicious SDKs (with honest intentions or not) can violate users' data privacy, damage app performance, or even cause apps to be banned from Google Play or the App Store.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] New technologies allow app developers to control and monitor client SDKs in real time.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] Providers of SDKs for specific systems or subsystems sometimes substitute a more specific term instead of *software*.
[src:android-jni/native-development-kit] For instance, both Microsoft and Citrix provide a driver development kit for developing device drivers.
